   {:e #blake3 "c68d3d4e8d1a3da718b21748f223dc6facf3244a9a5844d5352f922ba6205e17" :a :task/description :v "CONTEXT: Audit observations contain prose dependency references like 'interacts with F-INV-001', 'requires F-C8-001 as prerequisite', 'strengthens F-TYPE-001'. These are valuable dependency information locked in unstructured text. The dependency graph between findings is invisible to the query engine. RATIONALE: The trace scanner (trace.rs) already extracts spec references (INV-*, ADR-*, NEG-*) from source code text using regex. The same technique applied to observation bodies extracts cross-references between observations. Once extracted as datom refs, the dependency graph becomes queryable via the VAET index. APPROACH: (1) Create observation_links() function that scans :exploration/body text for patterns: task IDs (t-[0-9a-f]{8}), finding IDs (F-TYPE-NNN, F-INV-NNN, F-C8-NNN, etc.), and dependency keywords ('depends on', 'requires', 'prerequisite', 'interacts with', 'blocks', 'enables', 'strengthens'). (2) Classify links as :observation/depends-on (Ref, Many) for blocking deps and :observation/related-to (Ref, Many) for non-blocking relations. (3) Run during harvest pipeline after observation storage. (4) Expose via VAET index — braid query can traverse 'what depends on this finding?'. ACCEPTANCE: (A) After running on audit observations, the dependency chain from F-ERR-003 -> F-INV-001 -> F-TYPE-001 -> F-C8-002 is queryable via VAET. (B) observation_links() returns empty vec for observations with no cross-references. (C) Duplicate links are deduplicated. CONSIDERATIONS: Prose reference parsing is inherently fuzzy. False positives (matching 'F-TYPE' in unrelated context) are acceptable because the links are advisory, not constraining. False negatives are worse — missing a dependency means incomplete traversal. Favor recall over precision. DEPENDS-ON: t-7716255c (C9 EPIC). FILE: crates/braid-kernel/src/harvest.rs or new observation_graph.rs." :op :assert}
